Headlines.Headline: FDA Warns About Long-Term Problems With Blood-Clot Device

PARAGRAPH.#text: (Adds details from Archives of Internal Medicine study.) WASHINGTON (Dow Jones)--The U.S. Food and Drug Administration warned Monday that certain devices used to keep blood clots from traveling to the lungs could fracture and migrate to other parts of the body. Known as inferior vena cava, or IVC, filters, the small devices are inserted into the main vessel returning blood from the lower half of the body. The devices can be used to treat patients with venous thromboembolism, or blood clots in the legs, in order to keep the clot from traveling to the lungs where the clot can be fatal.
